  "prompt": "How is RMM calculated in chemistry?",
  "response": "RMM, or Relative Molecular Mass (also known as Molecular Weight), is calculated by summing the atomic masses of all the atoms in a molecule. Here's how you can calculate it:\n\n1. **Identify the Molecular Formula**: Determine the molecular formula of the substance. For example, water (H\u2082O) has two hydrogen (H) atoms and one oxygen (O) atom.\n\n2. **Find Atomic Masses**: Look up the atomic masses of each element from the periodic table. The atomic mass is typically in atomic mass units (amu). For example:\n   - Hydrogen (H) = approximately 1.01 amu\n   - Oxygen (O) = approximately 16.00 amu\n\n3. **Calculate the Contribution from Each Element**: Multiply the atomic mass of each element by the number of times that element appears in the formula:\n   - For water (H\u2082O): \n     - Hydrogen: \\( 2 \\times 1.01 \\, \\text{amu} = 2.02 \\, \\text{amu} \\)\n     - Oxygen: \\( 1 \\times 16.00 \\, \\text{amu} = 16.00 \\, \\text{amu} \\)\n\n4. **Sum the Values**: Add the contributions from each element to get the total RMM:\n   - Total RMM for water = \\( 2.02 \\, \\text{amu} + 16.00 \\, \\text{amu} = 18.02 \\, \\text{amu} \\)\n\nTherefore, the relative molecular mass of water (H\u2082O) is approximately 18.02 amu.\n\nIn summary, the RMM is calculated by:\n\\[ \\text{RMM} = \\sum (\\text{Number of atoms}) \\times (\\text{Atomic mass}) \\]\nfor all elements in the molecular formula.",
